===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
In the oracle bone and bronze scripts, it was an {{Han compound|丵|土|又|ls=ic|nocap=1|t1=tool for digging|t2=earth|t3=hand}}. The original meaning of the character is unclear, but it may be “to develop (land)”. It was later borrowed for “to reply”. Compare {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|封}}, {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|邦}}.

In the seal script, {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|又}} has become the related {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|寸}}. ''{{w|Shuowen}}'' has two seal script forms for this character: {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|𡭊}} (main form) and {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|對}} (alternative form). The main form, which has a {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|口|t=mouth}}, was probably created to specialize the character to signify “to reply”, but this form was not inherited in later scripts. ''Shuowen'' interprets the latter form (shown above) as a form that {{w|Emperor Wen of Han}} created by replacing {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|口}} with {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|士|t=soldier; warrior}} because many of the replies were untruthful (just [[lip service]]), but it is more likely that {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|士}} is a corruption of {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|土}}.

===Etymology===
[[exoactive|Exoactive]] of {{och-l|答|to reply; to answer}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

